# TypeScript And Performance Rule

- Write new code in TypeScript.
- Prefer immutable data (`const`, `readonly`) where possible.
- Prefer lower-allocation solutions when equivalent in readability.
- Use optional chaining (`?.`) and nullish coalescing (`??`) instead of verbose null checks.
- Avoid introducing avoidable CPU overhead in hot paths.

## How to verify

- Confirm changed source files are TypeScript (`.ts` or `.tsx`).
- Confirm no new mutable variables are introduced unless necessary.
- Confirm null handling uses `?.` and `??` where suitable.
- Confirm hot-path loops avoid unnecessary allocations.
